> If it is really cold right now where you live you might also be dealing
> with a carb that is freezing up.
>
> If not, be sure you have made a trip to the junkyard to accumulate the
> parts for a proper air cleaner and the hose they use to grab heated air
off
> of the exhaust manifold. I fought with one of these a few years ago for a
> friend and it was hell.
>
> Just look for anything with a carburetor. They all had factory "heated"
air
> cleaner arrangements. You'll have to find one that fits and they usually
> use a small vacuum line to move the flapper inside.
>
> At 07:54 PM 4/9/02 -0700, you wrote:
> >I'm with Pops on this one.  The rubber boots where the carb base plate
> >connects to the manifolds are notorious for leaking.  Check the clamps as
> >I've seen problems with the clamps failing and they look good but don't
> >apply much pressure to seal the rubber.  Get it to idle as low as you can
> >and spray some carb cleaner on 'em.  If the RPMs increase, voila.  Get
new
> >clamps (better yet, get new boots--their cheap).  This system is pretty
> >simple.  Should be easy to find the leak.
> >
> >Good luck,
> >Bill
